
Automating GIS-processes - Lecture 8: Python GIS
================================================

Converting text to Shapefile using Pandas/Geopandas
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

**Pandas** data analysis module is great for reading different file
formats (such as txt/csv, excel files, various databases etc.) into
pandas DataFrames. These features of pandas are very useful when the aim
is to convert different fileformats into spatial data such as
Shapefiles.

Next we test how social media data collected from Instagram can be
converted from text-file into Shapefile that we can easily use and
visualize e.g. in ArcGIS or create an interactive visualization as was
done in previous lecture.

Reading text into Pandas DataFrame
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

First we need to read the text file into pandas DataFrame that can be
done easily by using *.read\_csv* function.

Download and see how the Instagram data looks like from
`here <http://www.helsinki.fi/science/accessibility/data/Instagram/Instagram_sample.txt>`__.
It is important to first check what is the character separating the
columns from each other and see how the data looks like. In our case, we
can see that the columns are separated with tabulator
(':raw-latex:`\t`').

.. code:: python

    # Import necessary modules used in this lecture
    import pandas as pd
    import geopandas as gpd   # geopandas is usually shortened as gpd
    from shapely.geometry import Point
    from fiona.crs import from_epsg
    
    
    # Set filepath (in this case I download the data directly from the server where I have put the data)
    fp = r"http://www.helsinki.fi/science/accessibility/data/Instagram/Instagram_sample.txt"
    
    # Read file using pd.read_csv() and determine the separator
    data = pd.read_csv(fp, sep='\t')
    
    # Let's see what we got --> print the 'head' of the file (first 5 rows)
    data.head()

Cleaning the data from duplicates
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

There seems to be duplicates in the first rows of the dataset, so we can
assume that there might be also more duplicates in the rest of the
dataset. We don't want to have any duplicate rows, thus we will delete
such rows by using a nice pandas function called **.dropduplicates**.

.. code:: python

    # Drop duplicate values from the data set
    data = data.drop_duplicates()

Creating Geometries from the coordinates
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Before we can make a GeoDataFrame from our dataset we need to create
Shapely geometric objects from the coordinates. This can be done by
iterating over the rows and passing 'Latitude' and 'Longitude' values to
Shapely Point object which is updated to the column 'geometry'.

.. code:: python

    # Create an empty column for geometries
    data['geometry'] = None
    
    # Iterate over rows in data and make Point object from the coordinates
    for index, row in data.iterrows():
        # Get the coordinate values 
        x = row['Longitude']
        y = row['Latitude']
        
        # Create a Shapely Point object
        point = Point(x, y)
        
        # Add the Point object to the data's column 'geometry' at current index position
        data.ix[index, 'geometry'] = point
        
    # Let's see what happened
    data.head()

Creating GeoDataFrame from Pandas DataFrame
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Now we have created Shapely Point objects from the coordinates that were
present in the dataset. Next we have to convert the Pandas DataFrame
into Geopandas GeoDataFrame that makes it possible to write the data
into Shapefile. We also determine the coordinate system for the data.

.. code:: python

    # Creating a GeoDataFrame called 'geo' from Pandas DataFrame is straightforward
    # We pass the DataFrame into the GeoDataFrame and determine the column with Shapely Point objects and determine the crs
    geo = gpd.GeoDataFrame(data, geometry='geometry', crs=from_epsg(4326))
    
    # Let's see what we have
    geo.head()

Exporting data to Shapefile
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Finally, we can export the data using GeoDataFrames *.to\_file*
function.

.. code:: python

    # Determine the output path for the Shapefile
    out = r"C:\HY-Data\HENTENKA\Data\Instagram_points2.shp"
    
    # Fill NaN values before exporting (produces an error otherwise)
    geo = geo.fillna(-1)
    
    # Change the data type of 'User-ID' to integer (produces a warning otherwise)
    geo['User-ID'] = geo['User-ID'].astype(int)
    
    # Write the data into that location (use 'utf8' encoding for presenting the text)
    geo.to_file(out, encoding="utf8")
    
    # Produces a following warning, but it doesn't affect the result:

Extra - Create an interactive visualization of social media data using bokeh
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Following lines of code demonstrate how we can create an interactive map
of our Instagram Points on top of Google Maps using bokeh module. See
the result at the end of this page, you can zoom in/out and also move
around the map.

In the GIS-lab computers bokeh module is not installed, so unfortunately
at the moment it is not possible for you to test this yourself.

.. code:: python

    # Import bokeh stuff to visualize our map
    from bokeh.models.glyphs import Circle
    from bokeh.plotting import figure, show, output_notebook
    from bokeh.models import GMapPlot, Range1d, ColumnDataSource, HoverTool, PanTool, WheelZoomTool, BoxSelectTool, GMapOptions, ResizeTool
    from collections import OrderedDict
    
    # Plot the data using bokeh - Initialize
    output_notebook()
    
    # Parse coordinates into a list
    x_coords, y_coords = geo['Longitude'].values[:], geo['Latitude'].values[:]
    
    # Set the ranges for the map 
    x_range = Range1d(24.9, 25.0)
    y_range = Range1d(60.15, 60.2)
    
    # Set the Google Maps to Helsinki
    map_options = GMapOptions(lat=60.37, lng=24.952, map_type="roadmap", zoom=5)
    
    # Create an interactive Google map to Helsinki
    plot = GMapPlot(
        x_range=x_range, y_range=y_range,
        map_options=map_options,
        title = "Southern Finland - Instagram Points",
        plot_width=600,
        plot_height=500,
        webgl=True
    )
    
    # Create a Data source
    source = ColumnDataSource(
        data=dict(
            lat=y_coords,
            lon=x_coords
            
        )
    )
    
    # Create the Patch i.e. the polygon
    circle = Circle(x="lon",y="lat", fill_color='#DE2D26', size=1.2)
    
    # Add Polygon Patch on top of the map
    plot.add_glyph(source, circle)
    
    # Add tools
    plot.add_tools(PanTool(), WheelZoomTool())
    
    # Show the map
    show(plot)
